Investor FAQs | US Investment Network | Investor Resources Toggle navigation United States Investment Network Investors How It Works Investor FAQ Angel Investment Tips Sign Up as an Investor Entrepreneurs How It Works Entrepreneur FAQ Business Proposal Tips Add Your Pitch Explore Search Pitches Browse Investors Blog Tools & Resources Help Investor FAQ Entrepreneur FAQ About Us Contact Us Sign In Sign Up Investor FAQ Frequently Asked Questions Do I have to do my own due diligence on companies I like? We highly recommend doing your own due diligence on companies you wnat to invest While we do perform vetting of the enetrpreneurs we allow to participate in our network, there is still research that should be done outside of the We will do everything we can to keep scammers off the platform, but the users are ultimately responsible for vetting the quality of their own What happens if a company I want to invest in does not meet its funding target? The US Investment Network platform does not function as a crowdfuding Not reaching a specific goal will not result in project These specific details are left for the two parties to decide for on their own, outside of the Are investments completed through the site? Our platform does not support Our goal is to facilitate relationships between interested investors and motivated Once the initial contact has been established, the subsequent investment transaction takes place directly between you and the entrepreneur (not via our website). Why are entrepreneurs not responding to me? There are a few reasons this could be the case including a lack of information in your For more information, see our help section on creating a professional profile on the US Investment Network How do I get in touch with entrepreneurs? When you see a pitch that you want to follow up on, simply click “I m Interested”. This will automatically send a message to the entrepreneurs and notify them of your From here, you can exchange contact info and continue to correspond as you see Can I prioritize certain types of pitches? Our search filters can prioritize the investment criteria to the type of pitches you want to focus Where do investment pitches come from? The pitches we receive are submitted by individual entrepreneurs, companies, and incubators from our networks all over the You can use search filters and profile settings to prioritize what types of pitches appear in your Who can use this platform? The US Investment Network is designed to be utilized by sophisticated investors and professional All users who sign up are subject to a review process where we try our best to filter out illegitimate profiles and unqualified As an investor, you are free to browse pitches within our network but will not be able to contact entrepreneurs until you are approved by the review How is my privacy protected? Important contact information is only shared with parties you connect with and choose to share this info All other details you provide are always kept How much does the US Investment Network cost? The platform is free to use for Is there an investment minimum or maximum? No, there is no The size of funding rounds varies depending on the needs of the entrepreneur and the outlook of their business - we have clients looking to secure funding rounds of all United States Investment Network Follow us on social media About How it Works About Us Contact Us Navigation Investor Directory Search Pitches Investor Tips Investor FAQ Business Proposal Tips Entrepreneur FAQ Additional Info Where to Find Angel Investors Angel Investors in Chicago Angel Investors in Houston Angel Investors in Seattle Angel Investors in Colorado Angel Investors in Florida Angel Investing in NYC Angel Investors in Atlanta Angel Investors in the SF Bay Area Angel Investors in Miami Angel Investors in Arizona Angel Investors in Dallas Copyright © US Investor Network LLC, all rights | Terms of Use | Privacy Policy | Sitemap   Tips for Investors | US Investment Network | Quick Guide Toggle navigation United States Investment Network Investors How It Works Investor FAQ Angel Investment Tips Sign Up as an Investor Entrepreneurs How It Works Entrepreneur FAQ Business Proposal Tips Add Your Pitch Explore Search Pitches Browse Investors Blog Tools & Resources Help Investor FAQ Entrepreneur FAQ About Us Contact Us Sign In Sign Up Angel Investment Tips The Basics Angel investing is one of the most important aspects of any economy, and most people will agree that it is an important factor when it comes to boosting Put simply, angel investing is the provision of capital by an individual to a business (usually a startup) in exchange for equity or convertible Angel investors are different than venture capitalists, as they are putting forth their own private funds whereas venture capitalists have a pool of money to work Angel investors may decide to invest for a variety of They may discover a brilliant idea at a very early stage, they may thrive on starting n

Educational Materials | Home Explore Sign In Educational Materials Last updated - ​ INTRODUCTION TO FANDED AND CROWDFUNDING ​ Fanded Funding Portal LLC (“Fanded”) is a platform that will facilitate crowdfunding for professionals in the entertainment and media Fanded’s mission is to empower up and coming and established artists with resources by allowing fans to invest in their next Fanded has created a platform that gives artists the opportunity to sell ownership of their next project to any willing A project can be anything from an artist’s next album, music tour, music video or all of the By doing this, artists are provided with up front capital to execute their project without funding Crowdfunding is a new and evolving method for individuals and small companies looking to raise capital using the Companies and individuals employing crowdfunding are usually looking to raise smaller amounts of capital from a larger group of This is contrary to traditional model where small companies focus on a single financier to provide “seed” or “start-up ” The Securities and Exchange Commission (“SEC”) adopted rules to permit companies to offer and sell securities through crowdfunding in reliance on the exemption under Section 4(a)(6) of the Securities Act of (“Securities Act”). These new rules implement the requirements of Title III of the Jumpstart Our Business Startup (“JOBS”) Act, which added Sections 4(a)(6) and to the Securities Act and Sections 3(h) and (g)(6) to the Securities Exchange Act of (“Exchange Act”). A “funding portal” is a Title III crowdfunding intermediary that, in accordance with Section (b) ofthe JOBS Act and Exchange Act Section 3(a)(80), can engage in specially enumerated crowdfunding OUR FUNDING PORTAL AND PROCESS We are a Funding Portal that is registered with SEC and a member of We are not a or an investment Funding Portals are a virtual marketplace (i.e., an intermediary) that connects companies that wish to raise capital through securities offerings with individuals who are seeking investment As a Funding Portal, we cannot and will not: Offer investment advice or recommendations Solicit purchases, sales or offers to buy the securities offered on our platform Compensate employees, agents, investors, or entities seeking investment capital other persons for such solicitation or based on the sale of securities displayed or referenced on its funding portal or Hold, manage, or handle in any manner investor funds or Issuer Relationships We create business relationships with companies that wish to raise capital (i.e., “issuers”) who pay us for access to our funding Our relationships with an issuer may be related to a securities offering or for multiple securities offerings over longer period of Following completion of an offering, there may or may not be any ongoing relationship between the issuerand the funding We may receive compensation from issuers in the form of payment (e.g., monies or securities) as a percentage of funds raised on our funding portal, a flat fee, or in other Investors may refer to the issuer’s respective offering documentation (e.g., Form C) that is found on our portal and the SEC’s EDGAR website ( https: www.sec.gov edgar searchedgar companysearch.html ) for additional Types of Securities Displayed and Associated Risks The securities offerings listed on our portal are private securities offering, which are also known as “non- public offerings”. These offerings are not publicly listed on an Exchange (e.g., New York Stock Exchange) and are not assigned a As a private offering, the securities listed on our platform are subject to risks, including the risk of loss of principal and there may not be a secondary market to sell the The securities displayed on our Funding Portal may include the following types of securities: Equities: Equity securities (e.g., common stock) represent an ownership interest of a company by Unlike holders of debt securities (e.g., bonds) who generally receive only interest and the repayment of the principal, holders of equity securities are able to profit from capital Capital gains is an increase in the value of a capital asset, such as a stock, that gives it a higher worth than the purchase The risks associated equity securities include, Risk of Loss, Market and Liquidity Risk, Performance Risk and Dilution Please see the subsequent section for explanations of these risks, Debt: Debt securities (e.g., bonds) may be issued by corporations as a method of making large purchases that they could not afford under normal An issuance of a debt security gives the borrowing corporation the ability to borrow money from investors in exchange for a promise to pay back the money at a later date, usually with The risks associated debt securities include, Risk of Loss, Liquidity Risk, Interest Rate Risk, Inflation Risk, Credit Risk and Call Risk if there is a call feature on the Please see the subsequent section for explanations of these risks, Convertible Securities:

for use either during a particular browsing session (a “session” cookie) or a future browsing session (a “persistent” or “permanent” cookie). “Session” cookies are temporarily stored on your hard drive and only last until they expire at the end of your browsing “Persistent” or “permanent” cookies remain stored on your hard drive until they expire or are deleted by Local shared objects (or “flash” cookies) are used to collect and store information about your preferences and navigation to, from, and on a cookies are set by the website you’re visiting, and they can only be read by that cookies are set by a party other than that Other Similar Technologies In addition to cookies, there are other automatic data collection technologies, such as Internet tags, web beacons (clear gifs, pixel tags, and gifs), and navigational data collection (log files, server logs, ) that can be used to collect data as users navigate through and interact with a For example, web beacons are tiny graphics with unique identifiers that are used to understand browsing In addition, UTM codes are strings that can appear in a URL when you move from one web page or website to The string can represent information about browsing, such as which advertisement, page, or publisher sent the user to the receiving What Cookies and Similar Technologies Are in Use and Why Do We Use Them? This is a single page guide and to search for specific query or section, just press CMD+F (macOS) or CTRL+F (Windows Linux) to open browser s default search Once you are logged in, you ll see a simple interface — the panel is used for generating content and the side is the editor to play around with the generated Writing Process 🔗 Language 🔗 Rytr supports + languages: 🇦🇪 Arabica 🇨🇳 Chinese 🇨🇿 Czech 🇩🇰 Danish 🇳🇱 Dutch 🇺🇸 English 🇫🇮 Finnish 🇫🇷 French 🇩🇪 German 🇬🇷 Greek 🇮🇱 Hebrew 🇮🇳 Hindi 🇮🇩 Indonesian 🇮🇹 Italian 🇯🇵 Japanese 🇰🇷 Korean 🇳🇴 Norwegian 🇵🇱 Polish 🇵🇹 Portuguese 🇷🇴 Romanian 🇷🇺 Russian 🇪🇸 Spanish 🇸🇪 Swedish 🇹🇭 Thai 🇹🇷 Turkish, The language has to be selected from the Select Language list which will appear on the left side of the Rytr Unlike other similar tools, we have a proprietary approach for supporting multiple languages that are not dependent on GPT3 limitations, allowing us to deliver a much better quality of We are adding new languages regularly, you can always reach out to us at for a special request and we will try our best to Tone 🔗 As a user, you have + tones you can select from (convincing, awestruck, inspirational, ) to add personality to your It can be selected from a list next to the languages To understand more about what Tone of Voice is and how it can be used check out our article on the Importance of Tone in Content Here are a couple of examples using different tones: Use Cases 🔗 Rytr supports + use cases already and new ones are added For a full list and detailed explanation of each one please refer to this use cases page . Once you select a use case, you will see a caption under each use case to understand what each use case is Please read these captions to get a better Here is an example: Input 🔗 Each use case offers an input field where the user is expected to type some text to give some context to the Small and informative phrases key points to the AI tool will act as a hint and helps the tool understand your needs 💡Useful tips 🔗 Follow the format shown in the placeholder text 🔗 Placeholder text gives you an idea about the kind of text you should provide to get the best results from the Follow the suggested character limit 🔗 The input text has a character limit that ranges from characters depending on the use case selected by Please provide as much input as you can to get specific
